WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:04.050
This is a photo of me in my first year of
school.

00:00:04.050 --> 00:00:13.970
There are about 38 children in this class
and, of whom, six survived.

00:00:13.970 --> 00:00:16.730
My name is Lydia Tischler.

00:00:16.730 --> 00:00:20.009
I’m 88-years-old.

00:00:20.009 --> 00:00:33.730
From September ‘42 until May ‘45, I was
in various concentration camps.

00:00:33.730 --> 00:00:35.390
Auschwitz was hell.

00:00:35.390 --> 00:00:37.090
Auschwitz really was hell.

00:00:37.090 --> 00:00:40.890
We were on the last but one transport to Auschwitz.

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:47.550
The last transport were all the prominents
in Terezin who went straight into the gas

00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:48.550
chamber.

00:00:48.550 --> 00:00:51.490
There were about 50 of us in a cattle truck
with a bucket.

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:52.740
That was it.

00:00:52.740 --> 00:01:02.740
We arrived in the middle of the night and
in Auschwitz you could smell the fear.

00:01:02.740 --> 00:01:05.309
You really could smell the fear.

00:01:05.309 --> 00:01:10.740
And we had to go through selection which - we
didn’t know it was selection but that’s

00:01:10.740 --> 00:01:11.740
what it was.

00:01:11.740 --> 00:01:18.640
Mengele, of whom you may have heard, was standing
there and he looked at you and then sent you

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:20.500
to the left or to the right.

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:25.450
The left was the side for living and the right
was the side for gas.

00:01:25.450 --> 00:01:33.841
I knew that our mother... because she didn’t
come to the left she went to the right.

00:01:33.841 --> 00:01:40.929
But after the war I sort of hoped that maybe
she was in some displaced persons’ camp.

00:01:40.929 --> 00:01:42.479
You know, that she wasn’t dead.

00:01:42.479 --> 00:01:45.060
That somehow, by a miracle, she escaped.

00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:53.819
We were herded into a huge hall and told to
undress.

00:01:53.819 --> 00:01:57.470
And then somebody came and shaved all our
hair.

00:01:57.470 --> 00:02:06.680
And then we were herded into another room
where we were sat on benches like in a theatre,

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:07.680
stacked.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:14.340
And, by then, people who had been there for
some time told us, you know, you will go to

00:02:14.340 --> 00:02:23.080
the gas chambers and so we sat there and,
I must say, I sat there and didn’t know

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:26.410
whether it would be water or gas.

00:02:26.410 --> 00:02:28.879
It was water.

00:02:28.879 --> 00:02:36.439
I remember when I came to Auschwitz in this
room that they took everything away from us,

00:02:36.439 --> 00:02:49.910
there was a wooden board with the nationalities
of all the nationalities that were in camp.

00:02:49.910 --> 00:02:54.689
And I think on top, I don’t think there
were any English people, French.

00:02:54.689 --> 00:02:59.580
And the bottom two were the Gypsies and the
Jews.

00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:04.390
And I remember, I have to remember this.

00:03:04.390 --> 00:03:13.420
For some reason it seemed to me important
where they are putting us.

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:19.370
Day to day life someone - one just took every
day as it came.

00:03:19.370 --> 00:03:23.180
I worked in the market gardens.

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:27.300
We were able to smuggle sometimes some of
the fruit.

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:33.121
For instance, cucumbers, if they were nicely
bent, you could stick it into your bra and

00:03:33.121 --> 00:03:35.709
bring it into the camp.

00:03:35.709 --> 00:03:45.439
And, luckily, nobody was taking our clothes
off to see what we had hidden.

00:03:45.439 --> 00:03:49.390
Potatoes you could put in your stockings.

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:55.609
Tomatoes were not safe because they could
squash and that was it.

00:03:55.609 --> 00:04:01.700
Paradoxically, I got acquainted with cultural
life in Terezin.

00:04:01.700 --> 00:04:11.870
You know, music, there were of course all
of the well-known actors, musicians, writers,

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:15.219
professors were also in camp.

00:04:15.219 --> 00:04:24.180
So there was a rich cultural and intellectual
life, as far as it was possible.

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:29.840
I heard Verdi’s Requiem for the first time
in my life in Terezin.

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:35.789
I would not have heard it if I had been at
home at the age of 12 in Ostrava.

00:04:35.789 --> 00:04:41.050
Life, for people like me, wasn’t the worst.

00:04:41.050 --> 00:04:49.900
It was much worse for older people who felt
the hunger and felt, you know, they had already

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:56.270
had a life that they were deprived of.

00:04:56.270 --> 00:05:04.460
Usually, when people have to deny something,
it’s because they have to deny something

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:10.720
because he’s a nasty man and he doesn’t
want to feel nasty so he has to deny that

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:15.330
anybody - you know, he perhaps would have
like to do it himself.

00:05:15.330 --> 00:05:22.800
This is how I understand, when people have
to deny the horrors.

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:32.700
In fact, when I came to England and I managed
to find a school and went to Brondesbury and

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:35.169
Kilburn high school for girls.

00:05:35.169 --> 00:05:40.090
And when the girls heard where I came from,
and they asked me questions, I thought, “How

00:05:40.090 --> 00:05:42.660
can they ask me these questions?

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:44.569
They’ve seen the films.”

00:05:44.569 --> 00:05:59.970
But, when I studied psychology, I understood
that, when things are so outside human experience,

00:05:59.970 --> 00:06:02.430
you really can’t believe it.

00:06:02.430 --> 00:06:09.060
We managed, I discovered late-on when I studied
psychology and psychoanalysis, how useful

00:06:09.060 --> 00:06:10.420
defences are.

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:13.730
You know, you could believe it and not believe
it.

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:16.090
You kind of told yourself, “No, they made
a mistake.

00:06:16.090 --> 00:06:18.699
It can’t be true.”

00:06:18.699 --> 00:06:25.520
So people just went to Auschwitz and very
few survived.

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:32.780
I think one person escaped from Auschwitz,
a Czech man who escaped and nobody believed

00:06:32.780 --> 00:06:40.450
him, what he told them.

00:06:40.450 --> 00:06:52.160
The best way to remember it would be if people
could learn from this experience so that it’s

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:53.539
not repeated.

00:06:53.539 --> 00:07:04.199
And, in fact, it’s something that I’ve
never felt that I needed to revenge myself.

00:07:04.199 --> 00:07:11.099
I also haven’t felt a victim.

00:07:11.099 --> 00:07:13.710
They didn’t succeed in making me a victim.

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:16.870
I’m a survivor which is something very different.

00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:25.319
We thought of them as inhuman but, I think,
they never made me feel that I’m less than

00:07:25.319 --> 00:07:26.319
human.

00:07:26.319 --> 00:07:31.919
I could, you know, I had to put up with what
they did to me.

00:07:31.919 --> 00:07:36.289
You know, when they told me to undress, if
I said “I’m not undressing” they’d

00:07:36.289 --> 00:07:38.979
have shot me or, I don’t know what they
would have done.

00:07:38.979 --> 00:07:47.189
And, although the Germans were able to take
away all my physical - almost everything,

00:07:47.189 --> 00:07:49.710
except my life, they left me alive.

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:55.570
But, you know, whatever could be removed from
my body, they removed from my body - they

00:07:55.570 --> 00:07:58.740
couldn’t remove my soul.

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:04.060
My soul, they couldn’t remove my integrity,
my inner-self.

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:06.900
That I managed to maintain.

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:15.349
All of us have, you know, all of us have the
capacity to be sadistic and horrible to other

00:08:15.349 --> 00:08:16.349
people.

00:08:16.349 --> 00:08:29.930
We manage to not do it, you know, but the
potential for destructiveness is in all of

00:08:29.930 --> 00:08:30.930
us.

00:08:30.930 --> 00:08:45.399
I actually believe that people are born - well,
they’re born neither good nor bad and that

00:08:45.399 --> 00:08:54.291
the badness is something that is the way someone
is treated as a child.

00:08:54.291 --> 00:09:00.570
That, if you’re treated well as a child,
you can’t become a Hitler.

